AB  - Buenos Aires's waste pickers bear a family resemblance to other economically pauperized, socially stigmatized and politically disenfranchised groups that make up the majority of residents who live and work in metropolitan regions of the Global South (Davis, 2006; Neuwirth, 2011). Although a significant number engage in what some scholars term needs-driven or survivalist politics, only a small faction of them advance their cause by relying primarily on the institutions of representative democracy: parties and social movements, mass media and public opinion, the judiciary and congress, elections and referendums, and associations and non-governmental organizations (NGOs). In his insightful study of everyday politics among the shantytown dwellers of Calcutta, Partha Chatterjee argues this breach between liberal democracy and subaltern groups has become dominant and widespread in most cities of the southern hemisphere and has transformed them into the new epicenters of "popular politics ... [where] political modernity is being forged today" (2004, p. x).
